g.text: PIT Runtime: Counter Cycle and IRQ0 Generation

text.tspan: We use 11 write lo byte then hi byte to 0x40
Mode 2: counter reloads automatically; IRQ0 fires reliably every N clocks
OUT 0x43, 0x36 arms Channel 0 for divisor load
Hardware constant cannot change in software
Write lo first, then hi to port 0x40
Value 0x36: Ch0, Lo+Hi access, Mode2 RateGen, Binary
Effect: PIT enters awaiting-divisor state for Ch0
Latency: 1-4 us (legacy ISA I/O port stall)
PIT stores low byte in internal latch
Counter NOT reloaded yet awaiting hi byte
OUT pin: HIGH HIGH HIGH ... HIGH LOW* RELOAD
*At count=1: OUT pin goes LOW (IRQ0 asserted to PIC)
*At count=0: Counter reloads with 11931, OUT goes HIGH
1. PIT OUT0 goes LOW asserts IRQ0 on master PIC
2. Master PIC checks IMR bit 0 (unmasked=0 required)
3. CPU finishes current instruction, checks IF=1
4. CPU sends INTA PIC returns vector 32
5. CPU indexes IDT[32] jumps to irq0 stub
6. irq_common_stub: pusha, load DS=0x10, call irq_dispatcher
8. pic_send_eoi(): outb(0x20, 0x20) clears IRQ0 ISR bit
volatile required: modified by IRQ handler,
read by polling code compiler must not cache.
OUT LOW pulse = 1 PIT clock = 838 nanoseconds
PIC latches the LOW transition as IRQ0 assertion
Counter immediately reloads N after reaching zero
From IRQ0 assertion to first handler instruction:
IDT lookup (L2 cache hit): ~10 cycles ~5 ns
Each channel: 16-bit Count Register + Output Latch
